                        <h2 class="txtColorBlue text-center  "><mark class="markSty-who highlight">History of Hydrography </mark></h2>


                        <div class="col-sm-12 p-3  bg-white ">
                            <p class=" phgJust">




                                The origin of hydrography dates back to the eighteenth century, particularly during the wars fought by the British against their enemies, where they noted that they had lost most of their warships, not because of their enemy's power, but because of navigational hazards or because of their collisions with rocks in shallow waters mainly because of the lack of accurate charts that could be used by all warships. By the end of the 18th century, and specifically on August 1795, the Royal British Navy Hydrographic Office was established. It is the first of its kind in this field.
                                <br /><br />


                                The production of modern charts containing the depths and dangers of the sea to ensure the safety of international navigation began in 1807, when thousands of nautical charts were issued. Two years after the publication of the charts, it was agreed that copies of the British charts would be sold to all the world's sea pioneers, which encouraged the UK Hydrographic Office to expand its surveys to include all the water bodies in the world. This has also encouraged other countries to take an interest in this field, especially by the end of the nineteenth century, where there was hardly a maritime country without hydrographic capabilities.


                            </p>
